initial_story:
The baby suffered a cardiac arrest at the theme park on Thursday

A woman has been arrested on suspicion of neglecting a five-month-old boy who suffered a cardiac arrest at a theme park.

The baby is in a critical condition in hospital following the incident at Legoland Windsor at about 13:00 BST on Thursday, police said.

A 27-year-old woman from Witham, Essex, was arrested on suspicion of neglecting a child to cause unnecessary injury.

She has been released on bail until 26 July.

Det Con Zoe Eele, of Thames Valley Police's Child Abuse Investigation Unit, said: "Firstly, our thoughts are with the family of the boy who is in a critical condition in hospital after suffering a cardiac arrest.

"We are working closely with the team at Legoland Windsor Resort but would like to speak to anyone who have information about this incident, specifically anyone who was queueing for the Coastguard HQ boat ride between around 11.30am and 12:45pm.

"I would ask for the public to please avoid speculation about the incident and to respect the boy's family at this deeply upsetting time."

Police said they are not looking for further suspects in relation to the incident.

In a statement, the theme park said: "On Thursday, a young guest was taken ill... and our fully trained First Aid team administered immediate care until the emergency services arrived.

"We will continue to support Thames Valley Police with their ongoing investigation."

stories: In addition to releasing the woman on bail, police are also reviewing security footage and statements from witnesses who were near the ride area at the time of the incident. Investigators are looking into the baby's condition before he suffered the cardiac arrest and are exploring all possible circumstances that may have led to the tragic event.

Authorities are working to determine if there was a malfunction in the ride's equipment, whether the baby's medical condition was exacerbated by the ride, or if another factor was responsible. The investigation is expected to take several days to complete, during which time the ride will remain shut down as a precautionary measure.

Meanwhile, the family of the child is receiving support from amusement park officials and a specialized crisis team, and has released a statement expressing gratitude for the outpouring of prayers and condolences received thus far.

"The family would like to thank the community for their understanding and compassion during this difficult time, and kindly requests that they respect their privacy as they navigate this tragic situation."

"As they continue to grieve the loss of their loved one, they ask that any memorial donations be made in their honor to the local children's hospital in recognition of the impact their smile and spirit had on countless young lives."

"In lieu of flowers, the family prefers donations to the 'Be a Star' pediatric cancer fund, a cause close to their heart. Checks may be made payable to the 'St. Lucy's Children's Hospital Fund' and sent to their attention."

"Memo line: "Be a Star Fund in [Name]'s Memory". To make donations online, please visit their website at stlucyschildrenshospital.org and use the password STARMEMORIAL. The family would like to take this opportunity to express their gratitude for your compassion and generosity."

"In their memory, your kindness will shine a light of hope for many others in need of medical care. We appreciate your generous contribution to help Children's Hospital continue to provide the highest quality care for our youngest patients. Your kindness will make a difference in the life of a child who is counting on us."

"This special child, who was helped by your thoughtful gift, will receive life-changing treatment and begin to recover from their illness, all thanks to the compassion and dedication of our medical team. We are grateful for your support in helping Children's Hospital create a brighter future for children everywhere."

"We were reminded once again of the importance of partnerships like yours, which allow us to provide hope and healing to families who might otherwise struggle to access the care their child so desperately needs."
"These ongoing collaborations are a testament to the power of communities coming together to make a difference in the lives of others, and we are truly grateful for your support."

"It is because of partnerships like yours that we have been able to witness tangible positive change in countless individuals and communities, and we look forward to continuing this journey together."
"Would you be available for a meeting next week to discuss the progress we've made and explore new ways to further our impact together?"
"I'd be happy to meet; when specifically were you thinking? And is there a particular topic or issue you'd like to focus on during the discussion?"
"Were you envisioning an in-person meeting or would online/video call work better for you? Additionally, did you have any specific questions or areas of improvement in mind for us to review?"

"In the meantime, the draft agenda for Friday's meeting is attached to this email. Please take a few minutes to review it and let me know if there are any topics you'd like to add or have more information on. I'm also happy to chat with you offline if you'd prefer that approach instead."
